  "text": "Histological sections of Ad28.gfap.atoh1-treated ears demonstrated hair cell regeneration in the organ of Corti compared to the untreated side (Figs. 4 and 5 ). There were, however, several structural irregularities. Supernumerary inner hair cells could be observed at 1 month following Atoh1 delivery (Fig. 4) . Additionally, the cells labeling in the outer hair cell region appeared to be in the region of the Hensen cells but not in the associated Dieters cells, which raises the question as to which supporting cells are actually undergoing transdifferentiation or producing new hair cells. At 2 months following Atoh1 delivery, inner hair cells could be demonstrated in the treated ear but not in the untreated side (Fig. 5) . Myosin-expressing cells were no longer seen in either group. The collapse of Corti's organ continued in the basal turn of the untreated side leaving a flat epilthelium that has previously been described in severe aminoglycoside injury in guinea pigs. [CITATION_1] As noted in the aforementioned study, the overly damaged epithelium does not appear to respond to Atoh1, possibly explaining some of the limits of hair cell recovery that are seen in this series of experiments.",
